    <h1>Investigation of pH Sensor Drift in Industrial Effluents</h1>
    <div class="meta">
        <strong>Date:</strong> Oct 2024 | <strong>Category:</strong> Environmental Metrology | <strong>Author:</strong> Your Name
    </div>

    <h3>1. Abstract</h3>
    <p>This study analyzes the stability of industrial pH probes exposed to acidic effluents over a 180-day period. The objective was to determine the optimal calibration interval to maintain ISO 17025 compliance.</p>

    <h3>2. Methodology</h3>
    <p>Three sensors (Brand A) were subjected to daily cycles of pH 4.0 and pH 10.0 buffers. Drift was recorded weekly against a primary standard reference material.</p>

    <h3>3. Key Results</h3>
    <p>The data indicates a linear drift pattern after Day 45.</p>
    
    <table class="data-table">
        <tr>
            <th>Time (Days)</th>
            <th>Avg Drift (pH units)</th>
            <th>Status</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>30</td>
            <td>0.02</td>
            <td>Pass</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>60</td>
            <td>0.08</td>
            <td>Warning</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>90</td>
            <td>0.15</td>
            <td>Fail (>0.10)</td>
        </tr>
    </table>

    <h3>4. Conclusion</h3>
    <p>To maintain uncertainty limits within ±0.05 pH, the calibration interval must be reduced from 90 days to 45 days. A new maintenance protocol has been proposed.</p>

